Zachary Ochuodho @zachuodho The cost of living shot up to 6.58 per cent on the back of increasing food prices. According to data released by the Kenya National Bureau of Statistics, increase in fuel prices also contributed to the surge in inflation. Although the increase was the steepest in the recent past, it still remained within the Central Bank of Kenya’s (CBK) target range of between 2.5 per cent and 7.5 per cent and comes after a span of one year and eight months. Maize flour The rise in inflation from 4.35 per cent registered in March marks a 51.3 per cent increase. In February, the inflation rate stood at 4.11 per cent – the lowest rate this year. KNBS director general Zachary Mwangi, sifted maize flour, sukuma wiki (kales), potatoes, loose maize grain, flour and tomatoes recorded increases of 29.8, 25.3, 19.3, 26.1, 15.9 and 15.5 per cent respectively in April. “The CPI increased by 3.51 per cent from 198.91 in March to 205.90 in April. The overall year on year inflation in April 2019 stood at 6.58 per cent,” said Mwangi. KNBS report indicates that between March and April 2019, food and non-alcoholic drinks’ index increased by 6.86 per cent. “The increase was mainly due to drought conditions which prevailed in the better part of April causing an upsurge in the costs of some foodstuffs,” he said. These six items alone account for 6.25 per cent of the consumer price index (CPI). However, prices of sugar and some other food items were lower in April than in March. Housing, water, electricity, gas and other fuels’ indices increased by 0.95 per cent in April compared to March. The transport index increased by 0.86 per cent, mainly on account of increase in petrol and diesel pump prices.